{{Infobox artifact | name = Benin ivory mask | image = Queen Mother Pendant Mask- Iyoba MET DP231460.jpg | image_caption = This 16th century ivory portrait of Queen Mother [[Idia]] is among [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|The Met]]'s most celebrated works. It is one of four related ivory pendant masks, that were among the prized regalia of the [[Oba of Benin]], among the prestige items taken by the British during the [[Benin Expedition of 1897|punitive expedition of 1897]]. | material = Ivory, iron inlay | height = 9 3/8 in (23.8 cm) | width = 5 in (12.7 cm) | depth = 3 1/4 in (8.3 cm) | created = Early 16th century | location = [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], [[British Museum]], [[Seattle Art Museum]], [[Linden Museum]], private collection }}
The '''Benin ivory mask''' is a miniature sculptural portrait in [[ivory]] of the powerful [[Queen mother|Queen Mother]] [[Idia]] of the 16th century [[Benin Empire]], taking the form of an [[African traditional mask]].
Two almost identical masks are extant: one at the [[British Museum]] in [[London]] and the other at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/beta/asset/ivory-mask/YwEcUb_gRSUFrw|title=Ivory mask - Google Arts & Culture|newspaper=Google Cultural Institute|access-date=2017-02-24|language=en}}</ref><ref name="met">Metropolitan Museum Collection [http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/318622 Queen Mother Pendant Mask: Iyoba], MetMuseum, retrieved 1 November 2014</ref> Both feature a serene face of the Queen Mother wearing a [[Precious coral|beaded]] headdress, a beaded [[choker]] at her neck, [[scarification]] highlighted by iron [[inlay]] on the forehead, and all framed by the flange of an [[openwork]] tiara and collar of symbolic beings, as well as double loops at each side for attachment of the pendant.
There are also examples on the same theme at the [[Seattle Art Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.seattleartmuseum.org/eMuseum/code/emuseum.asp?collection=27202&collectionname=WEB:African&style=browse&currentrecord=1&page=collection&profile=objects&searchdesc=WEB:African&newvalues=1&newstyle=single&newcurrentrecord=2|title=Collections - SAM - Seattle Art Museum|website=www1.seattleartmuseum.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref> and the [[Linden Museum]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lindenmuseum.de/sehen/ausstellungen/afrika/|title=Linden-Museum - Afrika|last=Lindenmuseum|website=www.lindenmuseum.de|language=de|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref> and one in a private collection,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/28b807fe-0bd6-11e0-a313-00144feabdc0|title=Sotheby's to auction 'Oba' mask|website=Financial Times|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/sothebys-cancels-sale-of-looted-benin-mask-2171125.html|title=Sotheby's cancels sale of 'looted' Benin mask|date=2010-12-29|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=2017-02-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> all taken during the British [[Benin Expedition of 1897]].
The British Museum example in particular has also become a cultural emblem of modern [[Nigeria]] since [[FESTAC 77]], a major pan-African cultural festival held in 1977, which chose as is official emblem a replica of the mask crafted by [[Erhabor Emokpae]].<ref name=HDN />
{{anchor|Creation and context|Creation|Context|Background}}
== Origins == ===Three of the ivory masks=== <gallery mode="packed" widths="3000px" heights="300px"> Met Queen Mother Mask (cropped).jpg|[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York Idia mask BM Af1910 5-13 1.jpg| [[British Museum]], London Miniaturmaske, Edo.jpg|[[Linden Museum]], [[Stuttgart]] </gallery>
===Benin Empire=== In the early 16th century, the dynamic [[Esigie]] ruled the [[Benin Empire]] of the [[Edo people]] as its [[oba (ruler)|Oba]]. He came to power as [[Portuguese discoveries|Portuguese explorers]] [[first contact (anthropology)|first made contact]] with the empire. Trade and diplomacy with Europe brought Esigie and the Edo prosperity and regional influence as the empire traded pepper, ivory, local textiles, and slaves for brass, cloth, coral beads, and mercenaries for protection. Esigie engaged in two major conflicts. First, his half-brother fought a protracted civil war over the [[line of succession]] that would crown Esigie, the firstborn. Second, Esigie successfully defended against an invasion from the northern [[Igala Kingdom]] and captured their leader.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} Esigie rewarded his key political and mystical advisor during these trials, his mother [[Idia]], with the title of ''Iyoba'' ([[Queen mother#African monarchies|Queen Mother]])—the first in a tradition of Queen Mother advisors<!--commemorated in [[cast bronze]] statues and given their own palace in Uselu (village now in Benin City)-->.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=29}} The identification with Idia was made by Oba [[Akenzua II]] in the mid-20th century.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=26}}
===Ritual use=== The [[Oba of Benin]] commissioned works from his guild of ivory and wood carvers, the ''Igbesanmwan''. Their works were customized for their ruler, between the material connotations of ivory and the visual motifs in the carvings.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=21}} At least two of the masks feature Portuguese imagery (although this imagery outlasted the actual Portuguese presence)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8PDPDRgO4sC&lpg=PP1 |title=Royal Art of Benin: The Perls Collection in the Metropolitan Museum of Art|last=Ezra|first=Kate|date=1992-01-01 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=9780870996337|language=en}}</ref><ref name="coll" /> and thus were likely created during Esigie's early-16th century rule (possibly ca. 1520),<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VckaCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA478|title=Voyages in World History|last=Hansen|first=Valerie|last2=Curtis|first2=Ken|date=2016-01-01|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=9781305888418|language=en}}</ref> either during Idia's life or soon after her death.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} The similarities between the masks indicate that they were likely created at the same time{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} by the same artist.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} Their details match the comparable carving qualities of ivory spoons and [[salt cellar]]s commissioned during the same period,{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} the early period of [[Benin art]], the phase of strongest affiliation with Ife or [[Yoruba art]].{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=182}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CgIQc4ng0GoC&pg=PA394|title=Art of Oceania, Africa, and the Americas from the Museum of Primitive Art|last=Goldwater|first=Robert|date=1969-06-01|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|language=en}}</ref> Ivory works from Benin were mainly for the Oba to use in ritual.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=18}} The masks may have been used in ceremonies including the Ugie Iyoba commemoration of the Oba's mother, as well the Emobo purification ceremony to expel bad spirits from the land.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}}{{sfn|Ezra|1984|pp=20–21}}<ref name=ezra2>{{cite book|last1=Ezra |first1=Kate|title=The Pacific Islands, Africa, and the Americas|date=1987|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|location=New York|isbn=0870994611|page=84 |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0870994611|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> Similar [[Benin court and ceremonial art|pendant masks]] are mainly used in contemporary Emobo ceremonies focused on bad spirits, though the traditions of Emobo may have changed throughout history.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|pp=20–21}}
Four rungs on the side of the masks, above and below each ear, let the masks hang in suspension{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} and indicate that the masks were suspended from a cord,{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} though experts have disagreed on how they were worn.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}}{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} British Museum art historian [[William Fagg]] concluded that unlike the small brass pendant masks worn at the waist by modern kings, the ivory mask was likely worn around the neck. An 1830s drawing of a similar mask worn at the breast by a neighboring ruler confirms Fagg's theory.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} Based on the position of the rungs, Metropolitan curator Alisa LaGamma also affirmed the theory.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} Benin specialist and anthropologist Paula Ben-Amos, however, wrote that the masks were worn on the waist as pendants during the Ugie Iyoba and Emobo ceremonies.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} The hollow masks likely served as [[amulet]]ic containers.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} Below the mask's collars, the ring of small loops are attachment points for [[crotal bell]]s.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8PDPDRgO4sC&pg=PA153|title=Royal Art of Benin: The Perls Collection in the Metropolitan Museum of Art|last=Ezra|first=Kate|date=1992-01-01|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=9780870996337|language=en}}</ref>
{{anchor|Description}}
== Description and interpretation == They are made of ivory, long and ovular in shape,{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|pp=26–28}}<!--fewer pages?--> and thinly carved, approaching semiopaqueness.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=21}} The similar British Museum and Metropolitan pendant masks have elaborate ornament at their hair and collar. Each mask's gaze is accentuated with iron inlay at its pupils and lower eye outline, and the eyes are slightly diverted by the eyelids.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|pp=26–28}}{{refn|The Met's mask uses iron inlay in the pupils and forehead markings, and copper inlay for the eyelid outline.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}}}} This use of inlay departed from the ways in which Europeans used ivory.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} Above the eyes, the four [[Supraorbital ridge|supraorbital]] marks are associated with Benin women.{{sfn|Ben-Amos|1980}} The masks' facial features are symmetrical and skillfully precise.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} Their lips are parted, nostrils slightly flared, and hair dense with tiny coils and a rectilinear hairline.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} The masks' expression of "impersonal coolness" reflected the stylistic conventions of the Oba's ivory carvers guild, with a naturalism typical of craft in early Benin art.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}}
===A powerful woman===
The depiction of women is rare in [[Benin art]],<ref name="met" /> though the position of [[Idia]], known to [[Edo people|Edo tradition]] as "the only woman who went to war", is exceptional, and the very title of ''Iyoba'' or Queen Mother was created for her.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/pwmn_3/hd_pwmn_3.htm|title=Idia: The First Queen Mother of Benin {{!}} Essay {{!}} Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History {{!}} The Metropolitan Museum of Art|last=Bortolot|first=Author: Alexander Ives|website=The Met's Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History|access-date=2017-02-24}}</ref> The headdress forms part of the ''[[ukpe-okhue]]'' ("parrot's beak") hairstyle she originated, and is more clearly seen on the [[Bronze Head of Queen Idia]].<ref name=":0" /> The depicted [[precious coral]] of the headdress and choker are in the form of cylindrical ''ikele'' ("royal") beads, which it was the specially-granted privilege of the Queen Mother to wear, being usually reserved for the Oba and the ''Edogun'' (war chief).<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EFI7tr9XK6EC&pg=PA527|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Women in World History: 4 Volume Set|last=Smith|first=Bonnie G.|date=2008-01-01|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=9780195148909|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8PDPDRgO4sC&pg=PA41|title=Royal Art of Benin: The Perls Collection in the Metropolitan Museum of Art|last=Ezra|first=Kate|date=1992-01-01|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=9780870996337|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vm9JAQAAIAAJ|title=The Art of Benin|last=|first=|date=2010-01-01|publisher=British Museum Press|year=|isbn=9780714125916|location=|pages=13|language=en|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtQP5why918C&pg=PA267|title=A Companion to Gender History|last=Meade|first=Teresa A.|last2=Wiesner-Hanks|first2=Merry E.|date=2008-04-15|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470692820|language=en}}</ref> The Linden Museum mask also has a string of actual ''ikiele'' beads of coral wrapped around its forehead.<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|url=http://raai.library.yale.edu/site/index.php?globalnav=image_detail&image_id=7588|title=Die Altertümer von Benin|last=Luschan|first=Felix von|last2=Ankermann|first2=B|last3=Arthur Baessler-Stiftung|date=1919-01-01|publisher=De Gruyter|year=|isbn=|location=Berlin; Leipzig|pages=|language=German}}</ref> These red beads and red cloth, once reserved for leadership figures, have in modern times been popularly adopted as elements of Edo traditional dress.
[[File:Uniben culture day 2.jpg|thumb|200px|Modern [[Edo people|Edo]] women wearing ''ikele''-style beads.]] The foreheads of both masks were are inscribed with four vertical [[cicatrice]]s over each eye, with inlays of a pair of iron strips highlighting the [[scarification]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F3VJAQAAIAAJ|title=Africa|last=|first=|date=2001-01-01|publisher=Prestel|year=|isbn=9783791325804|location=|pages=74|language=en|quote=|via=}}</ref> Iron is also used in the pupils and rims of the eyes.<ref name=":1"/>
===Trade symbolism=== [[File:Detail of Portuguese merchant and mudfish from crown of Met's Queen Mother Pendant Mask- Iyoba (cropped).jpg|thumb|Detail of Portuguese merchant head and [[Protopterus|mudfish]]]]
Ivory, both then and now, connotes royal wealth, power, and purity.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=21}} Ivory, already a luxury commodity in Africa, became increasingly coveted with the growth of the European [[ivory trade]].{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=14}} When an elephant was killed in Benin, the Oba received one tusk as a gift and was offered the other in sale. Thus, the Oba had many tusks and controlled the ivory trade.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=16}} Ivory is associated with the [[Edo people|Edo]] [[orisha]] of the sea, [[Olokun]]. As this orisha gives wealth and fertility, it the spirit world's equivalent of the Benin Oba. Ivory gave wealth similar to Olokun, as it enticed the Portuguese merchants who, in turn, returned wealth to Benin.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=16}} The Portuguese belonged to Olokun, having arrived from the sea.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=18}} The whiteness of ivory also reflects the symbolism of white chalk, whose ritual purity is associated with Olokun.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=16}}<ref name="ezra">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0870994611|title=The Pacific Islands, Africa, and the Americas|date=1987|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=0870994611|location=New York|page=84|last1=Ezra|first1=the Metropolitan Museum of Art ; introductions by Douglas Newton, Julie Jones, Kate|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uMv0CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT689|title=Encyclopedia of African Religion|last=Asante|first=Molefi Kete|last2=Mazama|first2=Ama|date=2008-11-26|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=9781506317861|language=en}}</ref>
The [[openwork]] of the tiara and collar represent tiny heads of Portuguese men in the tiara of both the Met and the British Museum examples, with eleven figures in the British Museum mask, and in the Met mask seven figures of Portuguese men alternating with six representations of mudfish, the [[West African lungfish]].<ref name=":3" /> The Portuguese, who had only recently arrived in the area, were a symbol of power and affluence to the royal court.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} Their iconography is identifiable by their long hair, hanging mustaches (often described as bearded), and domed hats.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=21}}<!-- Ezra identifies the heads as soldiers, not merchants --> Benin art historian Barbara Blackmun interprets these crown adornments as a reference to Idia's ability to conduct the Portuguese power to her son's favor.{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=29}} Mudfish were a common theme in Benin royal arts,{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} and reflected the divinity of the Oba.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=18}} Edo cosmology believed that spirits crossed the ocean to reach the afterlife, where their leaders lived like gods. As creatures who could live on land and sea, the mudfish symbolized the [[Dualistic cosmology|duality]] needed for the leader's final journey,{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}} and this duality represents the seafaring Portuguese as well.<ref name="met" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6s6QN-rVWcIC&pg=PA119|title=The Art of Africa: A Resource for Educators|last=Clarke|first=Christa|last2=Arkenberg|first2=Rebecca|date=2006-01-01|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=9781588391902|language=en}}</ref> The mudfish also appear in a pattern on the Linden Museum mask's crown, while the private collection mask's crown has bird elements, also formerly present on the similar Seattle Art Museum mask.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} The masks also differ in pattern along their bottom, collar edges. The collar of the Met example is similarly decorated with eleven Portuguese men (with damage on its proper right side), while the collar of the British Museum mask is instead an abstract [[guilloché]] [[latticework]].{{sfn|LaGamma|2011|p=28}}{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}}
== Provenance ==
{{Multiple image | direction = horizontal | total_width = 300 | image1 = Rawson.jpg | image2 = Oba-ovonramwen crop etc.jpg | footer = [[Harry Rawson]] ''(left)'' led the British 1897 [[Benin Expedition]] to kill [[Ovonramwen]], [[Oba of Benin]], and destroy the kingdom's towns and villages. The ivory pendant masks were looted from the Oba's bedroom. }}
During the 1897 [[punitive expedition|punitive]] [[Benin Expedition]],<!-- https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/sep/11/2 --> the British found a group of similar ivory masks in the Oba's palace [[bedroom]]. The expedition's civil leader [[Ralph Moor]] took the two finest masks, which were later collected by British anthropologist [[Charles Gabriel Seligman]] and transferred to the London [[Museum of Mankind]] (now the [[British Museum]]) and the New York [[Museum of Primitive Art]] (now the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]). Two additional masks from the bedchamber group were taken by British officers and now reside in the collections of the [[Seattle Art Museum]] (formerly [[Principal Medical Officer]] Robert Allman) and the [[Linden Museum]] in [[Stuttgart]] (formerly [[W. D. Webster]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://raai.library.yale.edu/site/index.php?globalnav=image_detail&image_id=7588|title=Negro. Anthology made by N. Cunard, 1931-1933. [With illustrations.|last=Cunard|first=Nancy|date=1934-01-01|publisher=Nancy Cunard|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=|language=English}}</ref> and then [[Augustus Pitt Rivers]]),{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=182}} and there is one in a private collection of the heirs of [[Henry Galway]].<ref name=":4" />
Five to six masks of this type<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aSVQAQAAMAAJ|title=Divine Kingship in Africa|last=Fagg|first=William Buller|date=1978-01-01|publisher=Trustees of the British Museum|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=29|language=en|quote=|via=}}</ref> were found in a large chest in 1897 in the bedchamber of the then-reigning Oba [[Ovonramwen]], the ruler at the Benin court. They were taken at a time of great civil unrest during the British punitive [[Benin Expedition of 1897]], the British burned the royal palaces of the Oba and the Queen Mother and looted thousands of ivory, brass and wood from the [[Benin ancestral altars|ancestral altars]], private quarters and storerooms and many were sold in England to western museums and collectors to offset the cost of the expedition.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qK5bre18YkQC&q=198#v=snippet&q=oba%20benin%201897&f=false|title=Beyond Primitivism: Indigenous Religious Traditions and Modernity|last=Kaplan|first=Flora Edouwaye S.|date=|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2014|isbn=9780415273190|editor-last=Olupona|editor-first=Jacob Kẹhinde|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=Sacrifice and Sanctity in Benin}}</ref><ref name=":4" /> The British Museum's pendant was purchased in 1910 from the British anthropologist Prof [[Charles Gabriel Seligman]].<ref name=coll>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=621190&partId=1&people=163890&peoA=163890-1-6&page=1 British Museum Collection], British Museum, retrieved 1 November 2014</ref>
{{Multiple image | direction = horizontal | total_width = 300 | image1 = Nelson Rockefeller.jpg | width1=1070 |height1=1540 |width2=4500 |height2=2934 | image2 = Henri Rousseau 010.jpg | footer = Rockefeller founded the Museum for Primitive Art. Its director claimed that the mask would become as recognizable as Rousseau's ''[[Sleeping Gypsy]]''. }}
The Met's mask was acquired in 1972 as a gift of [[Nelson Rockefeller]].<ref name=met/> He founded the [[Museum of Primitive Art]] in 1954 after the Metropolitan Museum did not reciprocate his interest in [[Precolumbian art]]. The museum collected works for their artistic—and not anthropological—value,{{sfn|LaGamma|2014|pp=4–6}} contrasting with the earlier history of [[African art in Western collections]]. The [[Queens College]] art historian [[Robert Goldwater]] became its director and recommended acquisitions.{{sfn|LaGamma|2014|pp=5–7}} His argument to collect the ivory pendant mask was among his longest, at the end of 1957. He called it "the best object of its kind known, nor will any others ever turn up". Goldwater wrote that the mask was higher in quality than the similar, renowned one owned by the British Museum. The mask, he predicted, would redefine the collection and go on permanent display, on par with the [[Museum of Modern Art]]'s well-known ''[[Sleeping Gypsy]]'' (1897) by [[Henri Rousseau]]. Rockefeller purchased the mask at a record price and unveiled it in September 1958. The purchase solidified a policy that Goldwater believed the museum should center around permanent collections of [[masterpiece|masterworks]].{{sfn|LaGamma|2014|p=7}}
== Legacy ==
[[File:Festac '77 Grand Durbar (22173986028) (cropped) 1.jpg|thumb|[[Festac 77]], a major cultural festival in Nigeria, united African nations under the Idia mask emblem ''(pictured on the right)''.]]
The Benin Pendant Mask has become an [[Cultural icon|iconic image]] of Benin art, and the [[British Museum]] version in particular was featured on Nigerian [[Nigerian naira|one Naira banknotes]] in 1973,<ref name=naira>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/learning/schools_and_teachers/resources/all_resources-1/wealth_of_africa.aspx The wealth of Africa], British Museum, retrieved 1 November 2014</ref> and was chosen as the official emblem of the pan-africanist [[FESTAC 77]] cultural festival in 1977, so that this design is often known in modern Nigeria as the FESTAC Mask.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ELdTDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA139|title=Cultural Property and Contested Ownership: The Trafficking of Artefacts and the Quest for Restitution|last=Hauser-Schäublin|first=Brigitta|last2=Prott|first2=Lyndel V.|date=2016-06-10|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317281832|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qZqsAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT485|title=A Companion to Modern African Art|last=Salami|first=Gitti|last2=Visona|first2=Monica Blackmun|date=2013-10-22|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9781118515051|language=en}}</ref> The Nigerian government was unsuccessful in securing a loan of the work from the British Museum, and commissioned Edo artist [[Erhabor Emokpae]] to recreate the mask as a 20-foot tall bronze centerpiece for the festival (on display at the [[National Arts Theatre]] since 1979).<ref name=HDN>{{cite book|editor1= Falola, Toyin|editor2=Ann Genova|chapter=World Black and African Festival of Arts and Culture|title=Historical Dictionary of Nigeria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWTd1ftuCbwC&pg=PA369|date=2009-07-01|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6316-3|page=369}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/02/festac-40-history-mystery-behind-mask/|title=FESTAC at 40: The history and mystery behind the mask |date=2017-02-27|work=Vanguard News|access-date=2017-02-28|language=en-US}}</ref> He also designed a FESTAC flag<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cABTci1ARN0C&pg=PA61|title=The Pan-African Nation: Oil and the Spectacle of Culture in Nigeria|last=Apter|first=Andrew|date=2008-10-01|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226023564|language=en}}</ref> with the mask as central charge on an unequally banded black-gold-black [[Canadian pale|vertical tricolor]], and being responsible for the event's extensive graphic design.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/nigerianartistsw00kell|title=Nigerian artists : a who's who and bibliography|last=Kelly|first=Bernice M.|last2=Stanley|first2=Janet L.|last3=Smithsonian Institution. Libraries. National Museum of African Art Branch|date=1993-01-01|publisher=London ; New York : Published for the National Museum of African Art Branch, Smithsonian Institution Libraries, Washington, DC [by] Hans Zell}}</ref> Another Edo artist, [[Felix Idubor]], was commissioned to carve two replica masks in ivory for the [[Nigerian National Museum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1977/02/11/the-controversial-mask-of-benin/f6845f66-ffbd-40e5-8bc4-b7a551bdb8d0/|title=The Controversial Mask of Benin|last=Robinson|first=Alma|date=1977-02-11|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-02-28|last2=Robinson|first2=Alma|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> A 150&nbsp;kg bronze reproduction was also donated to UNESCO in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0013/001395/139543e.pdf|title=On the occasion of the unveiling of Queen Idia's Mask|last=Matsuura|first=Koïchiro|date=2005-05-25|website=UNESCO|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
The [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|Met]]'s Queen Mother pendant mask is considered among the museum's most celebrated works.{{sfn|LaGamma|2014|p=7}} African art historian Ezio Bassani wrote that the profile of the Met's mask was "at once delicate and strong" with a "musical rhythm", and that its use of iron and copper inlay was both "discreet and functional".{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} He wrote that the Metropolitan and British Museum masks were among the most beautiful ivories carved in Benin, and that their artist was both refined and sensitive.{{sfn|Bassani|1991|p=183}} Kate Ezra wrote that the mask's thinness showcased the "sensitivity and solemnity" of early Benin art.{{sfn|Ezra|1984|p=21}} <!--==Gallery== {{commons category|Benin Pendant Mask}} <gallery widths="300px" heights="300px" perrow="3"> File:Crop of Pendant Mask Iyoba Court of Benin.jpg|Detail of the Met mask </gallery> -->
