{{italictitle}}
{{For|the 11th-century ''gesta'' of the bishops of Liège|Heriger of Lobbes|Anselm of Liège}}
The '''''Gesta episcoporum Leodiensium''''' ("Deeds of the Bishops of Liège") is a history of the [[diocese of Liège]] written by the monk [[Gilles of Orval]] between 1247 and 1251.{{sfn|Pixton|1995|p=262}} At about the same time, Gilles also composed an epitome of his history, the ''Gesta episcoporum Leodensium abbreviata''.{{sfn|Pixton|1995|p=262}} It was first edited by Johannes Heller for the [[Monumenta Germaniae Historica]] in 1880.<ref>"Aegidii Aureaevallensis gesta episcoporum Leodiensium", MGH ''Scriptores'', 25 (Frankfurt: 1880), 1–129.</ref>

Gilles sought to continue the earlier ''gesta'' of [[Heriger of Lobbes]] and [[Anselm of Liège]] from 1048 down to 1247.{{sfn|De Grieck|2013}} As a historian, he was rather uncritical.{{sfn|De Grieck|2013}} His is the earliest account to mention any children of King [[Zwentibold]].

